      <hedline>
        <hl1>Thriving Despite AIDS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marla Hassner letter responds to Sept 20 article; disputes Housing Works lawyer Armen Merjian's contention that most people living with AIDS 'have no choice but to be on the dole'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Judge's Ruling Puts City AIDS Agency Under U.S. Monitor'' (front page, Sept. 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Judge's Ruling Puts City AIDS Agency Under U.S. Monitor'' (front page, Sept. 20):</p>
        <p>I commend Housing Works, the AIDS advocacy group that brought the suit resulting in the court's ruling, for its efforts in trying to improve access to services for people with H.I.V.-AIDS in New York City. But the comment by the group's staff lawyer, Armen Merjian, that most people living with AIDS ''have no choice but to be on the dole'' is a fallacy.</p>
        <p>Thousands of people with AIDS are able to work and engage in the same daily activities as people who are free of H.I.V. To equate an AIDS diagnosis with an inability to provide for oneself feeds a dangerous misconception and does a disservice to the countless people with H.I.V.-AIDS who are living, working and thriving despite their diagnosis.</p>
        <p>MARLA HASSNER  Brooklyn, Sept. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
